WEBVTT

1
00:01:07.300 --> 00:01:10.500
<i>Oh. I can't. I can't stay awake.</i>
<i>Stay awake. stay awake.</i>

2
00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:13.500
<i>Adderall. gone. Ritalin. gone.</i>

3
00:01:13.700 --> 00:01:15.000
<i>Amitriptyline. What is it?</i>

4
00:01:15.100 --> 00:01:18.800
<i>Modifinil. CNS. Dopamine.</i>
<i>A stimulant. Clonazepam.</i>

5
00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:21.900
<i>Clonazepam. good.</i>
<i>That's right. Yes. Good.</i>

6
00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:23.100
<i>Citric acid. yes.</i>

7
00:01:23.300 --> 00:01:26.200
<i>Oh. sugar. sugar. Fructose.</i>
<i>Mountain Dew. Mountain Dew.</i>

8
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Let us out! Please!

9
00:01:30.100 --> 00:01:33.700
<i>Who are those people? Who are they?</i>
<i>What are they trying to do to us?</i>

10
00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:35.600
<i>No one's ever gonna hurt my son.</i>

11
00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:37.900
<i>I can't stay awake. Please stay awake.</i>

12
00:01:38.100 --> 00:01:40.400
<i>Yes. you can. yes. you can.</i>
<i>I know you can.</i>

13
00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.600
<i>Stay awake. Yes. you can.</i>
<i>Come on. come on.</i>

14
00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:51.600
Let us out!

15
00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:56.200
Open the door! Open it! Open the door!

16
00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:15.500
<i>Tragic news tonight as</i>
<i>the space shuttle</i> Patriot <i>explodes...</i>

17
00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:17.900
<i>... during an unscheduled</i>
<i>landing attempt...</i>

18
00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:20.100
<i>We felt. you know. the explosion.</i>

19
00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:23.200
- <i>a trail of destruction and debris</i>
<i>from Dallas to Washington.</i>

20
00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:26.000
<i>Pieces all over the pasture</i>
<i>and in the yard. everywhere.</i>

21
00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:29.200
<i>Watching it. make sure nobody touches it.</i>
<i>nobody runs off with it.</i>

22
00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:32.000
<i>Why is it important for people</i>
<i>not to touch it?</i>

23
00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:34.200
<i>It's contaminated.</i>
<i>Could be contaminated.</i>

24
00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:37.600
<i>Of course. we all got out and we touched it.</i>
<i>some of us did.</i>

25
00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:39.700
<i>Crucial questions remain unanswered.</i>

26
00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:41.800
<i>Debris has been seen</i>
<i>from Dallas to Washington.</i>

27
00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:44.800
<i>The shuttle accident has shocked</i>
<i>the nation and the world.</i>

28
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
<i>Impromptu memorials can be seen</i>
<i>where debris has fallen.</i>

29
00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:49.700
<i>The scene here is surreal.</i>

30
00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:54.100
<i>We've seen a stream of officials from a</i>
<i>number of federal agencies coming through.</i>

31
00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:02.000
- Kaufman. CDC?
- That's right.

32
00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:03.200
Right this way. please.

33
00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:04.400
Mr. Kaufman!

34
00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:08.400
Dina Twain from CNN. Can I ask you what
the CDC is doing here. Mr. Kaufman?

35
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Hi. President's on his way back
to D.C. tonight.

36
00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:18.700
I'm supposed to brief him at 6 a.m.
Can we make that?

37
00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:22.400
- We can try.
- Right. Show me what you have.

38
00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.300
Over the retrieved debris...

39
00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:27.700
...we're recording a contamination rate
of almost every square meter.

40
00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:31.600
We're projecting a contamination zone
of an alley about 200 miles wide...

41
00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:34.100
...from D.C. to Dallas.
- My God. What is it?

42
00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:38.700
Our biotechs are in full meltdown mode.
This is a highly resilient organism...

43
00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:42.600
...able to survive the bitter cold of space
and the searing heat of reentry.

44
00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:46.200
Initial cellular diagnostics show
it exhibits monoploid characteristics...

45
00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:48.700
...with high levels
of calcium dipicolinate...

46
00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:50.900
...both commonalities to an endospore.

47
00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:52.800
A spore? Jesus.

48
00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:58.300
One thing's for sure.
it ain't from around here.

49
00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:06.100
Sir! This was on our roof.

50
00:04:18.900 --> 00:04:22.100
<i>The president is on his way back</i>
<i>to Washington from Camp David...</i>

51
00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:25.500
<i>... to meet with his closest advisors</i>
<i>over the space-shuttle disaster.</i>

52
00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:34.100
Hey. Casper.

53
00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:37.100
Good boy.

54
00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:44.100
I thought you'd never get home.

55
00:04:44.300 --> 00:04:46.200
Your ex-wife called twice.

56
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.800
Do you wanna watch this?
I mean. for work or something?

57
00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:51.900
I should get to bed.

58
00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:54.800
I gotta be back on the Hill
in a few hours.

59
00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:59.300
Well. you should've called. I could've
been sleeping in my own bed right now.

60
00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:04.900
<i>Federal officials are removing</i>
<i>several pieces of shuttle debris...</i>

61
00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:07.000
<i>... from a disturbing source: eBay.</i>

62
00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:06.100
Ollie!

63
00:06:06.300 --> 00:06:08.700
Ollie. it's okay. It's okay.

64
00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:11.300
Look at me. It's Mommy.

65
00:06:11.900 --> 00:06:13.500
Oh. baby.

66
00:06:13.700 --> 00:06:15.300
Oh. hey.

67
00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:17.100
It's okay.

68
00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:19.100
It's okay.

69
00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:21.300
You just had a bad dream.

70
00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:24.300
You got those nightmares
back again. huh?

71
00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:26.900
Everything's all right. You lie down.

72
00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:29.200
There we go.

73
00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:30.500
There we go.

74
00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:37.000
We'll just have to make those
nightmares go away again.

75
00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:38.900
Right?

76
00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:46.800
<i>Hundreds were killed this morning</i>
<i>in the bloodiest attack in Iraq...</i>

77
00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:48.800
<i>... since the start of the occupation.</i>

78
00:06:48.900 --> 00:06:52.100
<i>A mixture of toxic chemicals</i>
<i>was strapped to suicide bombers</i>...

79
00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:59.300
Ollie? Breakfast.

80
00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:07.800
<i>Dr. Bennell? I have a call for you.</i>

81
00:07:09.300 --> 00:07:10.800
I'm just finishing my notes.

82
00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:13.900
- <i>I know. but he is very insistent.</i>
- Who is it?

83
00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.800
<i>Your ex-husband.</i>

84
00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.600
- Hello?
- Carol. how are you?

85
00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:25.100
I'm fine. Tucker. How are you?

86
00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:28.000
I am fine. I'm really fine.

87
00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:32.500
I'm back in D.C. again.

88
00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:34.300
In our old house.

89
00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:37.100
It is such a nice house.

90
00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:40.600
What do you want. Tucker?

91
00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:42.500
I want to see Oliver.

92
00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:45.400
- <i>I miss him.</i>
- No.

93
00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:48.500
Carol. I have a legal right to see my son.

94
00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:56.100
Ollie. I don't believe it. Come on.

95
00:07:56.300 --> 00:07:58.600
Get dressed. We got 15 minutes.

96
00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.000
Come on.

97
00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:07.400
We should walk to school every morning.
This is nice.

98
00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:09.900
You wouldn't say that if it was raining.

99
00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:11.400
If it were raining.

100
00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:15.000
But what if it rains tonight?

101
00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:18.500
I checked the weather report.
Forty-five and clear. No rain.

102
00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:20.800
Just candy.

103
00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:23.100
Okay. here's your homework.

104
00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:25.800
- All right.
- You look cool.

105
00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:27.000
Thanks.

106
00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:29.000
- I'll see you at 4.
- All right.

107
00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:30.200
Can I give you a kiss?

108
00:08:36.800 --> 00:08:39.100
- Hey. Oliver!
- Nice costume. dude.

109
00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:41.000
I'm gonna get a double Hershey's bar.

110
00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:43.100
Oh. I wanna get as much chocolate...

111
00:08:43.300 --> 00:08:44.800
<i>America is in shock today...</i>

112
00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.800
50 scientists have resigned
over this shuttle debacle.

113
00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.100
- Good morning. Ben.
- Fifty. Five-oh.

114
00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:53.100
They signed a letter saying
the government's ignoring them...

115
00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:55.600
...because they think
the shuttle crashed on purpose.

116
00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:58.900
No one's reporting it here.
I had to find it on the World Service.

117
00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:03.200
What's wrong with you?

118
00:09:06.100 --> 00:09:08.700
Tucker takes off to Atlanta
for four years. Ben.

119
00:09:08.900 --> 00:09:11.600
He calls Ollie on his birthday
and at Christmas...

120
00:09:11.700 --> 00:09:16.600
...and suddenly he comes back into his life
and he wants to be a good father. No.

121
00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:19.900
It's confusing for Ollie.

122
00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:21.300
He is his dad.

123
00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:24.200
I know him. and I don't trust him.

124
00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:28.200
Look. Oliver loves you more
than anything else on earth...

125
00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:31.900
...and there is nothing that Tucker
or anybody else can do to change that.

126
00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:37.900
<i>Hard work! Fair pay! Hard work! Fair pay!</i>

127
00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:43.000
- Are we still on for tomorrow night?
- Will there be food?

128
00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:46.200
Well. they're Czechs. so there'll be.
what. goulash or something.

129
00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:48.400
We'll see.

130
00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:55.100
Spare some change. ma'am?

131
00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:56.600
God bless.

132
00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:03.900
Why would I get you flowers?

133
00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:07.100
Well. I didn't do anything wrong.
Hold on. hold on.

134
00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:09.000
That'll be 8 bucks.

135
00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:13.400
I am all about the romance.

136
00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:24.600
- Morning. Carly.
- Your 9:00 is here.

137
00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:37.800
You're a little early. Wendy.

138
00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:39.700
It's my husband.

139
00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:44.700
Wendy. did something happen?

140
00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:47.200
Did your husband hurt you again?

141
00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:50.700
How long have I been coming here?

142
00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:52.400
Four years.

143
00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:55.100
And I've had a cup of tea
almost every time. haven't I?

144
00:10:56.800 --> 00:10:58.300
Yeah. I suppose you have.

145
00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:01.100
But I can't do it.

146
00:11:04.100 --> 00:11:07.800
I can't even drink this.
That's how bad it's gotten.

147
00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:13.600
I wanna help you.
but you have to talk to me.

148
00:11:14.800 --> 00:11:18.100
This is gonna sound so stupid.
or crazy. or both.

149
00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:24.100
No. I've told you before. Nothing you say
in this office is stupid or crazy.

150
00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:27.100
All of it's important. All of it matters.

151
00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:30.700
My husband is not my husband.

152
00:11:32.600 --> 00:11:34.300
And what makes you say that?

153
00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:37.400
The way he acts.
The way he looks at me.

154
00:11:38.100 --> 00:11:40.100
He keeps bringing me things to drink.

155
00:11:40.300 --> 00:11:42.700
I don't want them.
but he keeps bringing them.

156
00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:46.400
I yelled at him last night.
He didn't yell back.

157
00:11:46.600 --> 00:11:50.000
I threw my glass at him
and he didn't do anything.

158
00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:52.800
I know you and your husband
have a volatile relationship.

159
00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
I did. but not anymore.

160
00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:59.500
Yes. when he would get mad.
I would be afraid of him.

161
00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:03.800
But at least when he kissed me.
I knew he loved me.

162
00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:06.400
Now when he kisses me...

163
00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:09.000
What is it?

164
00:12:09.700 --> 00:12:11.600
He's just different.

165
00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:14.800
I know it. Bobo knew it too.

166
00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:16.000
Bobo. your dog?

167
00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:20.900
The other night. when Richard got
home from work and he walked in...

168
00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:23.600
...Bobo. he just went crazy.

169
00:12:23.800 --> 00:12:26.500
He started snapping
and growling at Richard.

170
00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:29.500
I mean. we tried to put him outside.
but he attacked.

171
00:12:29.600 --> 00:12:33.500
Dr. Bennell. that dog has never
attacked anyone in its life.

172
00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:34.800
And what happened?

173
00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:37.800
Richard...

174
00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:41.600
...grabbed the dog's neck...

175
00:12:42.800 --> 00:12:46.600
...and Bobo just started whimpering.

176
00:12:47.300 --> 00:12:50.600
I tried to stop him.
but he wouldn't let go.

177
00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:53.900
And then. I could tell. Bobo. he...

178
00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.900
...he didn't understand what was
happening. He was so scared.

179
00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.400
And then there was this snap...

180
00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:02.200
...and Bobo was dead.

181
00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.200
Richard didn't say anything.

182
00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:07.500
He didn't cry.

183
00:13:08.600 --> 00:13:11.000
He just picked Bobo up...

184
00:13:11.100 --> 00:13:14.100
...and took him out to the garbage.

185
00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:24.100
I wanna see you again
as soon as possible.

186
00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:28.500
I'm gonna change your medication. I want
you to take these morning and night...

187
00:13:28.900 --> 00:13:30.800
...twice a day. Okay?

188
00:13:31.800 --> 00:13:36.200
And if your husband does anything like this
again. anything that frightens you at all...

189
00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:40.000
...I want you to call my service immediately.
Can you promise you'll do that?

190
00:13:40.500 --> 00:13:41.600
Yes. Thank you. doctor.

191
00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:46.100
That should work.

192
00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:50.100
Now. we should probably
talk about tomorrow.

193
00:13:52.300 --> 00:13:54.000
Are you nervous?

194
00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:55.600
Why would I be nervous?

195
00:13:55.800 --> 00:13:58.600
Because we've never
been apart like this. Ollie.

196
00:13:58.800 --> 00:14:01.600
And you haven't seen much
of your dad in a long time.

197
00:14:01.800 --> 00:14:06.000
I'm okay. Mom. It's gonna be fun.
But I'm gonna miss you.

198
00:14:06.200 --> 00:14:07.500
Yeah. you better.

199
00:14:07.700 --> 00:14:09.900
We can text each other all the time.

200
00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:14.200
You're right. I'm being silly. You go pack.

201
00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:17.000
We're gonna meet the Welches
in about half an hour.

202
00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:19.900
Go on. Superman.

203
00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:22.700
Thank you. Mrs. Robinson!

204
00:14:23.200 --> 00:14:24.300
Bye-bye.

205
00:14:24.500 --> 00:14:25.500
Thank you!

206
00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.600
Thank you.

207
00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:31.200
Trick or treat! Trick or treat!

208
00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:35.800
He's having nightmares again.

209
00:14:36.100 --> 00:14:38.900
I got him back on clonazepam.
I hate having him on anything.

210
00:14:39.100 --> 00:14:40.700
When did he start having them?

211
00:14:40.900 --> 00:14:44.800
The last three nights. Ever since
he's known he's gonna see his dad.

212
00:14:48.300 --> 00:14:50.700
Trick or treat! Trick or treat!

213
00:14:54.700 --> 00:14:56.000
Get back. boys.

214
00:14:57.600 --> 00:14:59.100
Stop that!

215
00:14:59.300 --> 00:15:02.400
She's been acting up. Maybe you
should take them to another house.

216
00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:07.300
I don't know what's wrong with her.

217
00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:08.700
Come on. boys.

218
00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:10.600
Let's go.

219
00:15:12.300 --> 00:15:14.000
- Blue. get back here!
- Watch it!

220
00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:16.600
Watch it!
Oh. my God. get him off!

221
00:15:17.600 --> 00:15:19.700
- Ollie. back!
- Blue! Get down.

222
00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:23.400
Down. girl. Bad dog. Bad dog!
I'm so sorry.

223
00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:26.200
- I'm so sorry.
- Andy! Andy. Oh. my God.

224
00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:31.200
He's fine. Pam.

225
00:15:31.400 --> 00:15:34.100
There's nothing there.
The blood must've been the dog's.

226
00:15:36.600 --> 00:15:37.600
Well.

227
00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:40.400
- Are you okay?
- Yeah. I'm okay. Mom.

228
00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:41.800
Okay.

229
00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.100
You took my candy.
Give me that Snickers!

230
00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:46.900
- That's mine.
- I want that.

231
00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.200
- No. you can have that.
- Give me that!

232
00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:52.800
- I'll trade you. Here. Russell's for Reese's.
- Oh. man.

233
00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:54.100
Thanks. Carol.

234
00:15:54.300 --> 00:15:56.500
How's Andy doing in school?

235
00:15:56.600 --> 00:15:58.100
He seems a little disconnected.

236
00:15:58.300 --> 00:16:01.800
Jeez. Carol. I mean. usually when
you start talking like a psychiatrist...

237
00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.800
...it's not about one of my children.

238
00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:10.300
Oh. he's just in a funk. You know. maybe
it's that bug that's been going around.

239
00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:12.700
- What's going around?
- Mom!

240
00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.100
Mom! Get this off of me. please! Mom!

241
00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:19.600
It's okay. it's okay. It's okay.

242
00:16:22.300 --> 00:16:24.600
- What is that?
- I think it moved.

243
00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:26.900
Did one of you put this here?

244
00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:29.400
- Not me.
- I didn't.

245
00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:34.300
Would you mind taking Gene home?

246
00:16:44.700 --> 00:16:45.700
Taxi!

247
00:16:52.300 --> 00:16:54.300
Carol. What are you doing here?

248
00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:56.500
Hey.

249
00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.900
That's for me?

250
00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:02.600
It's...

251
00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:06.600
I love it.

252
00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:10.700
There's no way of telling which house it
came from because we went to at least 30.

253
00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:14.000
I don't think there's anything
to worry about. It looks like latex.

254
00:17:14.200 --> 00:17:17.900
Ben. look at it. Even without a microscope.
you can see the cell strata.

255
00:17:18.700 --> 00:17:21.400
Well. maybe someone used
a finger as a mold.

256
00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:24.700
Someone's definitely made this
or bought it at Wal-Mart.

257
00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:27.900
I mean. it is Halloween.
It could be anything.

258
00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:32.300
What do you think. Steven?

259
00:17:35.500 --> 00:17:36.900
Interesting.

260
00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:38.400
It's manufactured. right?

261
00:17:38.600 --> 00:17:42.300
I don't know. It's either an expensive fake
or really cheap skin.

262
00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:45.400
Med Web's buzzing
with something like this.

263
00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:48.200
Labs in New York and Boston
logged some weird samples.

264
00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:49.700
Let me do a workup on it.

265
00:17:50.700 --> 00:17:53.000
- Thanks for helping. Steven.
- Yeah.

266
00:17:53.200 --> 00:17:54.800
Call me later. Ben.

267
00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.200
- You owe me an hour on your couch.
- An hour?

268
00:17:57.300 --> 00:18:00.000
What makes you think
anyone can help you in an hour?

269
00:18:03.300 --> 00:18:06.500
- What?
- I didn't say anything.

270
00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:10.900
<i>Each year. the flu claims</i>
<i>tens of thousands of American lives.</i>

271
00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:14.200
<i>You'd figure the government</i>
<i>would realize...</i>

272
00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:18.300
<i>... that we are facing nothing less</i>
<i>than a national medical emergency.</i>

273
00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:22.200
Our studies show this new virus
is more communicable...

274
00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:25.400
...and lasts longer than
more common strains of flu.

275
00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:28.200
<i>The CDC has begun</i>
<i>emergency meetings today...</i>

276
00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:31.000
<i>... to decide how to keep it</i>
<i>from getting any worse.</i>

277
00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:33.400
We think an inoculation program is our...

278
00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:37.000
Our best shot at keeping this
under our thumb.

279
00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:42.000
<i>This flu season could be</i>
<i>the deadliest in 30 years.</i>

280
00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:43.800
I'm curious.

281
00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:45.800
If you just cracked this new virus...

282
00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:48.300
...how are you ready
with vaccines so quickly?

283
00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:51.700
I wish there were more time to go over...

284
00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:55.400
...all of the science and the internal
processes behind this project.

285
00:18:55.500 --> 00:18:57.100
If you require more information...

286
00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:00.300
...l'd suggest you bow out
of this round of contracts...

287
00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:02.800
...and give us some time
to prepare a fact sheet.

288
00:19:03.400 --> 00:19:07.400
Is that what you'd like.
Mrs. Cunningham?

289
00:19:08.800 --> 00:19:11.100
Not at all. Just a question.

290
00:19:11.300 --> 00:19:12.900
Well. we like those.

291
00:19:13.100 --> 00:19:14.500
We like questions.

292
00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:16.700
They got you to the moon.

293
00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:32.800
Carol?

294
00:19:33.600 --> 00:19:36.500
That man wouldn't give a name.

295
00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:42.400
Can I help you?

296
00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:45.000
Dr. Bennell. I'm Richard Lenk.
Wendy Lenk's husband.

297
00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.100
What can I do for you. Mr. Lenk?

298
00:19:48.200 --> 00:19:50.000
I'm waiting for my wife.

299
00:19:50.300 --> 00:19:52.800
I don't think your wife
is coming in today.

300
00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:56.700
She said she was coming in.
but I'm bringing her home.

301
00:19:58.700 --> 00:20:02.000
Why don't you take a seat. Mr. Lenk.
and I'll see what I can find out.

302
00:20:02.100 --> 00:20:03.700
Thank you. Carol Bennell.

303
00:20:30.700 --> 00:20:35.100
- <i>Yes?</i>
- Wendy. it's Dr. Bennell. Where are you?

304
00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:37.900
<i>I am</i>... <i>I'm right outside your building.</i>

305
00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:40.100
<i>I need to talk to you.</i>

306
00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:43.500
<i>Or maybe I should talk to the police</i>
<i>if you think I should.</i>

307
00:20:43.600 --> 00:20:46.600
Wendy. your husband's here.
He's in the waiting room.

308
00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:49.700
He said you were coming in.
I didn't want you to be surprised.

309
00:20:52.900 --> 00:20:56.600
<i>Carol. can you keep him there a while?</i>

310
00:20:56.800 --> 00:20:58.900
- What are you gonna do?
- <i>I'll go home and pack.</i>

311
00:20:59.100 --> 00:21:00.200
<i>I'll stay with my sister.</i>

312
00:21:01.600 --> 00:21:03.800
I didn't know if I could trust you.
Thank you.

313
00:21:04.300 --> 00:21:05.900
Trust me?

314
00:21:06.100 --> 00:21:08.900
Wendy. Wendy.

315
00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:13.500
<i>Your 9:00 is here.</i>

316
00:21:13.700 --> 00:21:14.800
Send her in.

317
00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:17.300
<i>What about Mr. Lenk?</i>

318
00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:19.900
<i>Dr. Bennell?</i>

319
00:21:21.100 --> 00:21:22.800
Give him a magazine.

320
00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:27.700
Did you tell Gene
you're staying at your dad's...

321
00:21:27.900 --> 00:21:29.100
...starting tonight?
- Yep.

322
00:21:29.300 --> 00:21:31.900
It's a good thing
he still lives next door. huh?

323
00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:35.500
lmagine the pickle you'd be in if you
didn't know any kids in the neighborhood.

324
00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:36.800
Pickle.

325
00:21:37.700 --> 00:21:39.100
- Bread-and-butter.
- Dill.

326
00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:40.500
- Kosher.
- Sour.

327
00:21:40.700 --> 00:21:42.200
- Sweet and hots.
- Gherkins.

328
00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:44.000
Garlic chips. Perkies!

329
00:21:45.500 --> 00:21:47.000
That's not one.

330
00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:49.800
Come on. Perkies?

331
00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:51.100
Anyway. you already won.

332
00:21:51.200 --> 00:21:53.700
But why do people say
"in a pickle" anyhow?

333
00:21:53.900 --> 00:21:56.100
- I think it's a baseball term.
- Mom!

334
00:21:56.300 --> 00:21:57.500
Help me. please!

335
00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:01.100
Help me!

336
00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:02.800
They're coming!

337
00:22:03.400 --> 00:22:04.700
Listen.

338
00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:06.400
We've gotta warn people!

339
00:22:08.100 --> 00:22:09.800
They're among us! They're here!

340
00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
- Mom. what's wrong with her?
- Stop!

341
00:22:16.300 --> 00:22:18.700
Oliver. you listen to me.
You stay put.

342
00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:20.800
- All right?
- Okay.

343
00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:34.200
- Ma'am!
- I'm a doctor.

344
00:22:41.500 --> 00:22:44.800
Go back to your car.
I gotta clear the traffic out of this tunnel.

345
00:22:45.300 --> 00:22:46.700
I saw it happen.

346
00:22:46.900 --> 00:22:49.900
Where would you like me to wait
for a statement? I'm a witness.

347
00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:52.100
I took down your plates.

348
00:22:52.400 --> 00:22:54.800
Well. hold on.
Why did you take down my plates?

349
00:22:57.200 --> 00:22:59.400
Why did you take down my plates?

350
00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:02.100
If we need you. we'll be in touch.

351
00:23:11.100 --> 00:23:12.200
Hey.

352
00:23:12.400 --> 00:23:13.600
Sorry we're late.

353
00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:15.400
Hey. Oliver.

354
00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:18.200
He had a rough night.

355
00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:21.800
We saw an accident. It was terrible.

356
00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:23.100
It's okay.

357
00:23:25.100 --> 00:23:28.300
School starts at 8:10.
You have to have him there at 8.

358
00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:31.900
Do you want to come in?

359
00:23:32.400 --> 00:23:34.200
No. I'm late for a party.

360
00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:36.200
Enjoy the party.

361
00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:40.700
Make sure you take your pills.
One every night.

362
00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:42.800
Okay. Love you.

363
00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:04.800
It was awful.

364
00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:07.700
You should've seen her face.
She was terrified. Ben.

365
00:24:07.900 --> 00:24:10.800
And the police did nothing.
Absolutely nothing.

366
00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:13.000
I offered to give my name. be a witness.

367
00:24:13.100 --> 00:24:15.500
And Oliver. he saw the whole thing.

368
00:24:15.600 --> 00:24:17.400
Is he all right?

369
00:24:17.600 --> 00:24:20.800
I mean. he seemed all right.
but I had to leave him.

370
00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:31.900
We don't have to do this tonight.
I can take you home.

371
00:24:32.100 --> 00:24:34.400
No. I want to. I want to.

372
00:24:34.500 --> 00:24:37.300
- You sure?
- I'm good. yes. Let's have fun.

373
00:24:37.500 --> 00:24:39.600
This is meant to be fun.

374
00:24:39.900 --> 00:24:41.800
You look stunning.

375
00:24:43.300 --> 00:24:45.200
Good evening. Dr. Ben.

376
00:24:45.400 --> 00:24:47.500
- How are you?
- Fine. fine.

377
00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.400
- Oh. that might be Ollie.
- May I take your coat?

378
00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:52.800
- Thank you.
- The ambassador and his wife are waiting.

379
00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:56.200
<i>Hi. Mom.</i>
<i>I miss you. Gene wants to say hi.</i>

380
00:24:56.400 --> 00:24:57.700
<i>Hi. Miss Bennell.</i>

381
00:24:57.900 --> 00:24:59.900
- <i>Bye. I love you.</i>
- <i>Bye.</i>

382
00:25:01.800 --> 00:25:05.000
- May I take your coat. madam?
- Thank you.

383
00:25:08.300 --> 00:25:09.700
You are Carol.

384
00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:13.400
Carol Bennell. this is Dr. Henryk Belicec
and his wonderful wife. Luddie.

385
00:25:13.600 --> 00:25:17.900
Come here and let me see you.
Ben has told us a lot about you.

386
00:25:18.200 --> 00:25:21.700
Let us go in. Dinner will be ready soon.

387
00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:23.500
Now. you two sit with us.

388
00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:26.700
We want some real people
around us tonight.

389
00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:35.700
- Something's wrong with my dad.
- Yeah.

390
00:25:36.600 --> 00:25:38.400
Mine too.

391
00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:47.200
- Dad?
- In here. Oliver.

392
00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:54.800
I'm making some hot chocolate.

393
00:25:59.600 --> 00:26:02.000
Would you like some hot chocolate?

394
00:26:15.700 --> 00:26:19.900
So Ben tells me that
you are a psychiatrist.

395
00:26:20.100 --> 00:26:23.200
This is very interesting.
This is exactly what I need.

396
00:26:23.400 --> 00:26:26.600
You need what every Czech needs:
a stiff Russian boot up your behind.

397
00:26:26.800 --> 00:26:30.200
Pity they don't make Russian boots
anymore. They're all made in China.

398
00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:34.000
You seat me beside a beautiful woman
without introducing me. and you insult me.

399
00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:36.600
Oh. don't let him get started. Henyo.

400
00:26:36.800 --> 00:26:39.000
I'm sorry. Yorish. My humblest apologies.

401
00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:43.400
You have the honor of meeting one of
Washington's most notorious diplomats.

402
00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:47.500
My friend and the source
of this exquisite caviar...

403
00:26:47.700 --> 00:26:49.600
...Russian Ambassador
Yorish Kaganovich.

404
00:26:49.800 --> 00:26:53.400
- Nice to meet you. ambassador.
- The pleasure is entirely mine.

405
00:26:53.600 --> 00:26:56.400
Henryk's guests are usually
as old and as ugly as I am.

406
00:26:56.800 --> 00:26:59.300
I beg to differ.
No one's as ugly as you are. Yorish.

407
00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:02.600
You know what "Czechoslovakia"
means in Russian. doctor?

408
00:27:02.800 --> 00:27:04.400
It means a "doormat."

409
00:27:04.500 --> 00:27:07.500
Someone still speaks Russian?
I thought it was a dead language.

410
00:27:08.400 --> 00:27:12.300
My cheeky friend and I pretend to enjoy
ourselves. but secretly we are rivals...

411
00:27:12.500 --> 00:27:16.400
...exploiting each other for personal gain.
I am here to drink his champagne...

412
00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:19.600
...and he invites me
because I can get the real caviar.

413
00:27:19.900 --> 00:27:23.200
A veneer of civility hides
our true self-interests.

414
00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.300
It's the nature of our world. yes?

415
00:27:25.500 --> 00:27:27.000
Yorish. be good.

416
00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:28.500
I'm only curious.

417
00:27:28.700 --> 00:27:31.900
I say that civilization is an illusion.
a game of pretend.

418
00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:36.300
What is real is the fact that we are
still animals. driven by primal instincts.

419
00:27:36.500 --> 00:27:38.800
As a psychiatrist...

420
00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:40.600
...you must know this to be true.

421
00:27:40.700 --> 00:27:44.900
To be honest. ambassador. when someone
starts talking to me about the truth...

422
00:27:45.100 --> 00:27:47.300
...I hear what they
tell me about themselves...

423
00:27:47.500 --> 00:27:49.600
...more than what they
say about the world.

424
00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:52.000
- Quite right. Well done.
- Perhaps you are right.

425
00:27:52.200 --> 00:27:55.400
Perhaps being a Russian in this country
is a kind of pathology.

426
00:27:55.600 --> 00:27:58.300
So. what do you think? Can you help me?

427
00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:00.700
Can you give me a pill?

428
00:28:00.800 --> 00:28:03.800
To make me see the world the way
you Americans see the world?

429
00:28:04.100 --> 00:28:08.700
Can a pill help me understand Iraq.
or Darfur. or even New Orleans?

430
00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:11.500
Don't be drawn in
by his madness. doctor.

431
00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:14.700
He is Russian. He needs to argue
like he needs to breathe.

432
00:28:14.700 --> 00:28:18.600
All I am saying is that civilization
crumbles whenever we need it most.

433
00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.100
In the right situation...

434
00:28:22.300 --> 00:28:25.000
...we are all capable
of the most terrible crimes.

435
00:28:25.600 --> 00:28:27.900
To imagine a world
where this was not so...

436
00:28:28.100 --> 00:28:30.800
...where every crisis did not result
in new atrocities...

437
00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.900
...where every newspaper
is not full of war and violence...

438
00:28:34.100 --> 00:28:39.600
Well. this is to imagine a world
where human beings cease to be human.

439
00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:43.300
While I'll give you that we still retain
some basic animal instincts...

440
00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:47.100
...you must admit we're not the same
animal we were a few thousand years ago.

441
00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:49.400
- True.
- Read Piaget or Kohlberg...

442
00:28:49.600 --> 00:28:52.700
...or Maslow. Graves. Wilber.
and you'll see we're still evolving.

443
00:28:52.900 --> 00:28:54.900
Our consciousness is changing.

444
00:28:55.400 --> 00:28:58.200
Five hundred years ago.
postmodern feminists didn't exist...

445
00:28:58.300 --> 00:29:00.300
...yet one sits right beside you today.

446
00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:05.500
While that fact may not undo all the terrible
things that have been done in this world...

447
00:29:05.700 --> 00:29:09.100
...at least it gives me reason to believe
one day things may be different.

448
00:29:10.100 --> 00:29:12.800
- Thank you. doctor.
- You're welcome. ambassador.

449
00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:14.500
Excellent.

450
00:29:14.700 --> 00:29:17.400
Ben. of all the women
you've brought into our home...

451
00:29:17.500 --> 00:29:19.800
...this is the one
we permit you to marry.

452
00:29:19.900 --> 00:29:21.100
Hey. now. look.

453
00:29:21.300 --> 00:29:23.800
I've been watching
the way you look at each other.

454
00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:27.400
- Oh. so beautiful and smart.
- You see. this is what happens.

455
00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:31.500
They say what they like in this household.
and then they claim diplomatic immunity.

456
00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:34.300
- Think of the children you could have.
- Enough. Enough.

457
00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.300
I had a terrific time.

458
00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.200
Your friends are wonderful.

459
00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:56.300
Well. thank you for being my date.

460
00:29:56.500 --> 00:29:59.200
And for what you said tonight.

461
00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:13.200
What?

462
00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:28.800
No. I can't do this.

463
00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:30.200
No. That's...

464
00:30:30.400 --> 00:30:32.500
But that's... But that's fine.

465
00:30:33.900 --> 00:30:35.600
I'm sorry...

466
00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:38.000
...but I really need us
to stay what we are.

467
00:30:40.700 --> 00:30:43.600
You're my best friend.
and I can't lose that.

468
00:30:44.700 --> 00:30:47.000
Hey. Look. I...

469
00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:52.200
I just took advantage of a drunk woman.
and I'm sorry.

470
00:30:52.300 --> 00:30:54.100
- Now. can you walk?
- Hey!

471
00:30:55.200 --> 00:30:56.700
I can.

472
00:31:05.700 --> 00:31:07.200
Hey.

473
00:31:48.500 --> 00:31:49.600
Carol Bennell?

474
00:31:50.300 --> 00:31:52.000
I'm sorry to bother you so late.

475
00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:55.500
I need to ask you a few questions
for the Census Department.

476
00:31:55.700 --> 00:31:58.100
We're doing a census
of your district this month.

477
00:31:58.300 --> 00:32:02.300
Not the extended paper census. but a quick
door-to-door version to update our records.

478
00:32:02.500 --> 00:32:04.700
- At this time of night?
- Deadline.

479
00:32:04.800 --> 00:32:07.100
We're working all night now.
You're my last house.

480
00:32:07.300 --> 00:32:09.900
I saw your light. I came a few times.

481
00:32:12.200 --> 00:32:16.100
Listen. let me get that.
And then you can ask me through the door.

482
00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:24.800
Hey!

483
00:33:03.300 --> 00:33:08.000
<i>We're sorry. All circuits are busy.</i>
<i>Please hang up and try your call again.</i>

484
00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:16.100
Hey. Ben.

485
00:33:16.200 --> 00:33:17.900
It's me.

486
00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:22.800
I just... Somebody just scared
the shit out of me.

487
00:33:32.800 --> 00:33:34.000
Hey. Morning.

488
00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:35.600
Hey.

489
00:33:35.800 --> 00:33:38.600
- What did the police say?
- Not that much.

490
00:33:39.800 --> 00:33:43.000
- Carol. you're not going to work.
- I've got back-to-backs all day.

491
00:33:43.200 --> 00:33:45.800
At least stay and have some breakfast.
I cooked pancakes.

492
00:33:49.900 --> 00:33:51.500
What?

493
00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:56.200
<i>The thawing in tension between</i>
<i>Washington and Tehran...</i>

494
00:33:56.400 --> 00:34:00.500
<i>... over the enrichment of nuclear fuel</i>
<i>was one of the first steps...</i>

495
00:34:00.600 --> 00:34:02.400
<i>... by the U.S. to relax years...</i>

496
00:34:02.600 --> 00:34:05.000
<i>Morning. Mom. On the way to school.</i>

497
00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:07.500
<i>I still miss you. Love you. Bye.</i>

498
00:34:45.300 --> 00:34:46.800
Sorry I'm late.

499
00:34:48.700 --> 00:34:51.400
Courtney Jones canceled.
So did Chris Cook.

500
00:34:51.500 --> 00:34:53.100
What about Wendy Lenk?

501
00:34:53.300 --> 00:34:55.400
I haven't heard from her.

502
00:34:56.200 --> 00:34:59.100
Maybe it's that flu going around.

503
00:35:00.100 --> 00:35:02.000
I'll call her.

504
00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:11.200
Mr. Lenk. this is Dr. Bennell.
I was hoping I could speak with your wife.

505
00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:13.500
This is her cell phone I'm calling.

506
00:35:13.700 --> 00:35:15.300
<i>She's asleep right now.</i>

507
00:35:17.100 --> 00:35:19.600
Is everything all right. Mr. Lenk?

508
00:35:19.700 --> 00:35:23.300
<i>Everything's fine.</i>
<i>better than it's been in a long time.</i>

509
00:35:23.500 --> 00:35:24.900
<i>Wendy's fine now.</i>

510
00:35:25.100 --> 00:35:28.200
<i>I'll give her the message you called.</i>
<i>and she'll tell you herself.</i>

511
00:35:28.300 --> 00:35:30.200
- Mr. Lenk?
- <i>Yes?</i>

512
00:35:30.400 --> 00:35:34.500
If I don't hear from your wife soon.
I will be calling back. Do you understand?

513
00:35:34.800 --> 00:35:37.100
<i>You'll hear from her</i>
<i>by the end of the day.</i>

514
00:35:43.700 --> 00:35:44.800
It's my husband.

515
00:35:53.500 --> 00:35:55.500
Ben. they can't all be psychotic.

516
00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:03.000
<i>What if what they're saying is real?</i>

517
00:36:03.200 --> 00:36:05.200
Have you noticed anything?

518
00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:10.100
I have.

519
00:36:12.500 --> 00:36:14.000
What?

520
00:36:15.900 --> 00:36:17.700
He seems a little disconnected.

521
00:36:35.100 --> 00:36:38.800
- Hey. Carly.
- I thought you might like some tea.

522
00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:40.800
Thanks.

523
00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:45.300
Would you keep trying my ex-husband
until you get through? Okay?

524
00:36:45.400 --> 00:36:47.900
- It's important that I speak with him.
- All right.

525
00:36:48.100 --> 00:36:49.100
It's new.

526
00:36:49.800 --> 00:36:53.500
Like that orange pekoe you like.
Tell me what you think.

527
00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:03.600
Hey.

528
00:37:03.900 --> 00:37:05.700
Okay. dig this.

529
00:37:05.900 --> 00:37:09.300
Now. the best way I can describe
the sample that you brought me...

530
00:37:09.500 --> 00:37:12.500
...is a kind of post-infection sweat.
like a night sweat.

531
00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:15.400
Only. instead of evaporating.
this solidified.

532
00:37:15.600 --> 00:37:20.200
A percentage is spent white blood cells.
like you'd find in any normal infection.

533
00:37:20.300 --> 00:37:22.500
But. then. another percentage is...

534
00:37:22.700 --> 00:37:25.400
...hormones a body produces
when it enters REM sleep...

535
00:37:25.500 --> 00:37:28.100
...suggesting that the hormones
acted as a catalyst...

536
00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:31.600
...in some kind of metabolic reaction.
and then were expelled as waste.

537
00:37:31.600 --> 00:37:33.700
Yeah. but a reaction to what?

538
00:37:34.600 --> 00:37:37.100
A reaction to these.

539
00:37:38.600 --> 00:37:41.100
These are also spent cells.
Exploded. actually.

540
00:37:41.300 --> 00:37:44.700
- Are they viral?
- Viral-like. but larger than any virus known.

541
00:37:44.900 --> 00:37:47.000
Now. I tried to destroy some of them.

542
00:37:48.300 --> 00:37:53.100
I heated them up to see when they'd
incinerate. Took them up to 700 degrees.

543
00:37:53.200 --> 00:37:54.400
They survived.

544
00:37:54.600 --> 00:37:56.400
- Well. that's impossible.
- Yeah.

545
00:37:56.600 --> 00:38:00.000
Remember Ted Fraddo? He's out
at the lab at Fort Detrick now.

546
00:38:00.100 --> 00:38:02.800
They've settled on a hypothesis
that we're dealing with...

547
00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.200
...a complete. intelligent entity.
the dimensions of a few cells...

548
00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:09.100
...that's invading people's bodies.
integrating their DNA...

549
00:38:09.300 --> 00:38:11.600
...and reprogramming
their genetic expression.

550
00:38:11.800 --> 00:38:14.200
Reprogramming? How?
How would that look?

551
00:38:14.300 --> 00:38:17.800
Eighty percent of what we are
is determined by our genetic expression.

552
00:38:17.900 --> 00:38:20.900
Integration of alien DNA
could look like anything.

553
00:38:21.100 --> 00:38:22.700
Or nothing at all.

554
00:38:23.700 --> 00:38:26.000
So you say that this is
showing up all over?

555
00:38:26.100 --> 00:38:27.500
It's starting to.

556
00:38:27.700 --> 00:38:31.000
They began considering epidemic protocols
in Europe last night.

557
00:38:31.200 --> 00:38:34.800
Also in Japan. but here.
they're just talking about this flu.

558
00:38:39.500 --> 00:38:42.100
- Hello?
- Hello. Ben. This is Luddie.

559
00:38:42.300 --> 00:38:45.600
I'm so sorry to call you.
but I didn't know what else to do.

560
00:38:45.700 --> 00:38:48.400
- Well. what's happened. Luddie?
- <i>It's our friend Yorish.</i>

561
00:38:48.600 --> 00:38:50.200
Something's happening to him.

562
00:38:50.400 --> 00:38:52.000
<i>Something terrible.</i>

563
00:38:52.200 --> 00:38:53.300
We'll be right over.

564
00:38:56.500 --> 00:39:00.200
<i>The objective for today's G8 summit was</i>
<i>the concern of the medical community...</i>

565
00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:03.200
<i>... over the escalating cases</i>
<i>of this mysterious flu virus.</i>

566
00:39:03.300 --> 00:39:05.600
<i>Even more surprising</i>
<i>was the president's...</i>

567
00:39:05.800 --> 00:39:07.900
Tucker. it's me. Where are you?

568
00:39:08.100 --> 00:39:12.900
Call me as soon as you get this.
It's important that I speak to Oliver.

569
00:39:14.400 --> 00:39:15.400
Good. come in.

570
00:39:15.600 --> 00:39:18.300
Oh. Ben. Carol.
Thank you for coming so fast.

571
00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:22.200
- This is a colleague of mine. Dr. Galeano.
- Oh. doctor. Thank you.

572
00:39:22.300 --> 00:39:25.100
He came over. I couldn't work out
what was wrong with him.

573
00:39:25.300 --> 00:39:29.200
He didn't want to be near his wife.
He was worried about my husband.

574
00:39:29.400 --> 00:39:30.900
What did he say about Henryk?

575
00:39:31.100 --> 00:39:32.800
Where is your husband?

576
00:39:32.900 --> 00:39:35.200
I don't know.
I haven't been able to reach him.

577
00:39:36.900 --> 00:39:37.900
Oh. my God.

578
00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:40.200
- Jesus.
- Unbelievable.

579
00:39:40.400 --> 00:39:41.800
Oh. Yorish.

580
00:39:47.700 --> 00:39:49.900
He's so much worse. What is it?

581
00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:53.600
It's some kind of cellular condensation.

582
00:39:53.800 --> 00:39:57.300
Look at his carotid. His blood pressure
must be through the roof.

583
00:39:57.500 --> 00:40:00.600
Don't wake him. If he's in deep sleep.
it might hurt him.

584
00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:03.800
We'll need a complete diagnostic.
Record his vitals.

585
00:40:04.100 --> 00:40:06.500
Get blood and tissue samples.
Got any kit with you?

586
00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:07.900
Some.

587
00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:11.400
Luddie. we're gonna need a video camera.
Is there one in the press room?

588
00:40:11.600 --> 00:40:13.600
Carol. you've got a camera
in your phone.

589
00:40:19.900 --> 00:40:21.300
Get him off me!

590
00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:23.600
Get Yorish off her!

591
00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:26.400
Help her!

592
00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:44.400
Yorish!

593
00:40:49.300 --> 00:40:52.300
- I'm going to call the police.
- No. don't. Just...

594
00:40:53.400 --> 00:40:54.600
Don't call anyone yet.

595
00:40:54.800 --> 00:40:59.000
The REM-sleep interruption
must've caused his cardiac arrest.

596
00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:02.400
- Carol?
- I'm gonna get Oliver.

597
00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:16.700
- Carol.
- Check your messages. Tucker.

598
00:41:16.900 --> 00:41:19.000
I've been trying to get ahold of Ollie.

599
00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:21.400
Come in. Come in.

600
00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:24.200
These are colleagues of mine.

601
00:41:25.100 --> 00:41:26.200
Oliver!

602
00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:28.600
He's fine. He's with Gene.

603
00:41:30.300 --> 00:41:33.100
- Where you going?
- To get Ollie's things. He's coming with me.

604
00:41:36.600 --> 00:41:39.900
- You're very emotional right now.
- What's going on. Tucker?

605
00:41:40.100 --> 00:41:43.900
- Why don't you calm down?
- I just saw a man die.

606
00:41:44.100 --> 00:41:46.800
People are dying.
What are you really covering up. huh?

607
00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:51.300
What is it? You've got people lining up
like this is smallpox or something.

608
00:41:51.500 --> 00:41:54.700
What are you really
inoculating them for. Tucker?

609
00:41:55.700 --> 00:41:57.300
Tell me.

610
00:42:02.900 --> 00:42:04.300
Open the goddamn door!

611
00:42:05.700 --> 00:42:06.800
Open the door.

612
00:42:25.600 --> 00:42:26.800
What's going on here?

613
00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:30.000
When you wake up.
you'll feel exactly the same.

614
00:42:32.200 --> 00:42:34.400
- Oh. my God.
- You'll be the same.

615
00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:39.200
Every thought. memory. every habit...

616
00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:41.400
...will still be you.

617
00:42:41.500 --> 00:42:43.400
Don't fight. Carol.

618
00:42:44.300 --> 00:42:45.500
There's no need for it.

619
00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:49.700
All you have to do is nothing.

620
00:42:51.100 --> 00:42:53.100
That's all we're asking.

621
00:42:57.800 --> 00:42:59.700
It doesn't hurt.

622
00:43:01.700 --> 00:43:02.700
Watch.

623
00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:08.200
It's just like catching a cold.

624
00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:11.600
No! No!

625
00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:14.800
No!

626
00:43:16.300 --> 00:43:17.800
No!

627
00:43:18.600 --> 00:43:19.900
No!

628
00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:33.400
It's too late. Carol.

629
00:43:36.100 --> 00:43:39.000
- It's done.
- Oliver!

630
00:43:40.500 --> 00:43:42.500
Oliver!

631
00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:46.400
Help me! Help! Help me!

632
00:44:47.200 --> 00:44:49.800
Help! Help me!

633
00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:54.200
Please. help me! Please. help!
Help me!

634
00:45:05.500 --> 00:45:10.100
<i>Red Line service to Friendship Heights.</i>
<i>Adams Morgan. Dupont Circle...</i>

635
00:45:10.200 --> 00:45:12.600
<i>... Farragut North. boarding Track 3.</i>

636
00:45:22.400 --> 00:45:26.200
<i>Stand away from the doors.</i>
<i>Subway doors are now closing.</i>

637
00:45:35.500 --> 00:45:37.400
<i>Mom. I don't know where I am.</i>

638
00:45:37.600 --> 00:45:42.000
<i>Dad brought me here. I'm really scared.</i>
<i>Please come get me.</i>

639
00:46:01.700 --> 00:46:05.900
Try to calm down. You can fool them.
but you gotta calm down.

640
00:46:06.100 --> 00:46:09.400
- What?
- Don't show emotion.

641
00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:12.500
Then they can't tell who's who.

642
00:46:13.800 --> 00:46:15.700
- John.
- Stay calm.

643
00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:28.700
Jen. Jen. Jen.

644
00:46:28.900 --> 00:46:31.200
- Jen!
- Just leave us alone!

645
00:46:31.400 --> 00:46:33.100
What's wrong with you people?

646
00:46:33.300 --> 00:46:34.500
Come on. come on!

647
00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:54.800
Get the door open! Do it. do it!

648
00:47:00.200 --> 00:47:01.500
Come on!

649
00:47:12.100 --> 00:47:13.800
Come on! Jump!

650
00:47:15.800 --> 00:47:17.400
Jump!

651
00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:19.300
No! No!

652
00:47:19.700 --> 00:47:21.800
No! No!

653
00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:50.700
- Don't move.
- All right. miss. Slow down.

654
00:47:50.900 --> 00:47:52.800
Oh. God. You're one of them. aren't you?

655
00:47:54.300 --> 00:47:55.800
You don't wanna hurt anyone.

656
00:47:57.900 --> 00:48:00.900
I have a family. I have two boys.

657
00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:06.300
Oh. God.

658
00:48:41.400 --> 00:48:46.400
Don't sleep. don't sleep. don't sleep...

659
00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:50.300
No!

660
00:48:50.500 --> 00:48:52.200
Dad. no! Dad!

661
00:48:52.400 --> 00:48:56.000
No! Dad! Dad! Dad!

662
00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:08.500
You're sweating. They don't do that.
They'll know.

663
00:49:08.600 --> 00:49:09.800
Now go away from here.

664
00:49:15.300 --> 00:49:16.700
Dad!

665
00:49:35.100 --> 00:49:36.800
Next in line. please.

666
00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:38.300
Carol.

667
00:49:38.800 --> 00:49:40.500
Are you here for your shot?

668
00:49:42.300 --> 00:49:43.900
I had mine last night.

669
00:49:45.500 --> 00:49:46.800
I'm glad to hear that.

670
00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:48.900
Have you seen Oliver?

671
00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.100
I'm afraid I haven't.

672
00:49:58.400 --> 00:50:00.000
Ollie?

673
00:50:01.100 --> 00:50:02.900
Ollie?

674
00:50:03.900 --> 00:50:05.600
Ollie!

675
00:50:08.700 --> 00:50:10.000
Oliver!

676
00:50:13.300 --> 00:50:14.500
Ollie!

677
00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:00.200
No! No!

678
00:51:02.600 --> 00:51:04.800
What are you doing? No!

679
00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:06.800
No! No!

680
00:51:24.600 --> 00:51:28.500
I can't find him. I can't find him. Ben.
I can't find him.

681
00:51:28.600 --> 00:51:31.700
I can't find him.
I've looked everywhere. and I can't...

682
00:51:31.900 --> 00:51:34.200
- I can't find...
- We're gonna find him.

683
00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:39.200
It transmits like a virus or bacterium...

684
00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:42.400
...through exchange of fluids.
a kiss. an injection.

685
00:51:42.600 --> 00:51:45.000
Fort Detrick went into
lockdown mode this afternoon.

686
00:51:45.200 --> 00:51:48.800
They're running simulations now.
The numbers they estimate are incredible.

687
00:51:49.200 --> 00:51:52.100
Tens of millions may be infected
in the U.S. alone already.

688
00:51:52.300 --> 00:51:54.300
How can we know
if we've got it inside us?

689
00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:57.900
We can't. We just have to make sure
we stay awake.

690
00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:00.400
The change occurs when the body
undergoes REM sleep.

691
00:52:00.600 --> 00:52:03.300
We'll watch each other.
make sure we don't fall asleep.

692
00:52:03.500 --> 00:52:07.200
Fort Detrick is 50 miles from here.
We get down there. they'll take us in.

693
00:52:07.400 --> 00:52:09.400
I'm not going anywhere without my son.

694
00:52:10.400 --> 00:52:14.100
Carol and I'll go and find Oliver.
Then we'll meet you at Fort Detrick.

695
00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:17.000
Look.

696
00:52:22.300 --> 00:52:25.000
Where did you go? I was worried.

697
00:52:27.200 --> 00:52:29.000
Oh. God.

698
00:52:29.600 --> 00:52:33.500
You've always trusted me.
We've never been apart.

699
00:52:34.800 --> 00:52:38.200
You have to come to me.
or we can't be together.

700
00:52:41.800 --> 00:52:43.200
I need you.

701
00:52:45.700 --> 00:52:47.400
Henyo.

702
00:52:57.200 --> 00:52:59.300
Are there other people in the house?

703
00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:30.300
Form a line.

704
00:53:30.500 --> 00:53:33.600
Take a seat on the buses.

705
00:53:33.800 --> 00:53:39.200
Stay within the barricade.
Thank you for your cooperation.

706
00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:46.600
We should turn around.
We should not go there.

707
00:53:46.700 --> 00:53:48.700
No. They'll notice.

708
00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:52.800
Just stay calm. keep walking.
look them straight in the eye.

709
00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:55.200
- Stop it! Let go!
- Stay where you are!

710
00:53:55.400 --> 00:53:58.500
I know what's going on!
We don't have to go with them!

711
00:53:58.700 --> 00:53:59.800
Get on the ground. ma'am.

712
00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:03.300
I've been asleep.
Don't you get it? I've already slept.

713
00:54:03.700 --> 00:54:05.500
That's one of my patients.

714
00:54:05.700 --> 00:54:07.000
Would you let go of me?

715
00:54:07.700 --> 00:54:09.900
Help!

716
00:54:12.600 --> 00:54:14.600
Let's go.

717
00:54:14.700 --> 00:54:16.300
Good luck.

718
00:54:19.400 --> 00:54:22.500
She was saying she slept.
Did you hear her?

719
00:54:22.600 --> 00:54:26.500
So if she slept and she were infected.
that would mean she was immune.

720
00:54:26.600 --> 00:54:29.500
Possibly. There might be something
in her medical records.

721
00:54:29.700 --> 00:54:31.400
Do you keep them in your office?

722
00:54:31.500 --> 00:54:32.600
Yeah.

723
00:54:32.800 --> 00:54:36.500
<i>215. are you still requesting backup</i>
<i>for a traffic stop at Hampshire and M?</i>

724
00:54:37.200 --> 00:54:41.000
<i>Yes. dispatcher. we've got</i>... <i>215. we need</i>
<i>backup as soon as you can. Over.</i>

725
00:54:42.500 --> 00:54:45.700
<i>Copy. 215. ETA five minutes.</i>

726
00:54:53.100 --> 00:54:56.100
<i>All units. please be advised.</i>
<i>inoculations have begun.</i>

727
00:54:56.300 --> 00:55:00.700
<i>Scout 42. see the National Guard commander</i>
<i>at 56th Street to assist in crowd control.</i>

728
00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:02.400
<i>Copy. ETA five minutes.</i>

729
00:55:20.700 --> 00:55:25.000
Here's what I have. G.P. notes should be
in there. I'm gonna check the computer.

730
00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:29.500
I think her husband
transformed very early.

731
00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:33.100
- What kind of medication was she on?
- She was on BuSpar and clonazepam...

732
00:55:33.200 --> 00:55:35.700
...and I recently prescribed Risperdal.

733
00:55:36.100 --> 00:55:38.100
Oh. Jesus. how ridiculous.

734
00:55:38.300 --> 00:55:42.300
Her husband's infected with an alien virus.
and I prescribe an antipsychotic.

735
00:55:42.500 --> 00:55:46.200
Yeah. well. I thought that sample
you brought me was a Halloween gag...

736
00:55:46.500 --> 00:55:48.000
...so who's to know?

737
00:55:48.100 --> 00:55:51.300
That's interesting. She had encephalitis
when she was a child.

738
00:55:51.400 --> 00:55:54.800
- Yeah. it almost killed her.
- It onset as a varicella complication.

739
00:55:55.500 --> 00:55:59.100
- Her sister gave her the chickenpox.
- It might not be normal encephalitis.

740
00:55:59.200 --> 00:56:02.900
There's acute disseminated
encephalomyelitis. which is ADEM.

741
00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:06.800
It affects substantia alba. the brain's
white matter. as opposed to gray matter.

742
00:56:06.900 --> 00:56:10.700
It could be the reason why the virus
hasn't been able to attack her system.

743
00:56:11.600 --> 00:56:13.500
Well. we need to find her.

744
00:56:14.100 --> 00:56:15.800
- Are you all right?
- Three years ago...

745
00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:17.400
...Oliver got the chickenpox.

746
00:56:17.600 --> 00:56:20.000
He'd had his shots.
but it was a new strain...

747
00:56:20.100 --> 00:56:22.600
...and in the middle of it.
he had horrible dreams.

748
00:56:22.800 --> 00:56:25.600
His temperature skyrocketed.
he was hallucinating.

749
00:56:25.800 --> 00:56:28.200
I took him to the hospital.
They diagnosed him with...

750
00:56:28.400 --> 00:56:29.700
ADEM.

751
00:56:29.900 --> 00:56:32.900
- Do you think Ollie might be immune?
- It's a possibility.

752
00:56:33.100 --> 00:56:36.000
He's been at Tucker's for two nights
and he's still texting you.

753
00:56:36.200 --> 00:56:37.500
That could be the reason why.

754
00:56:37.700 --> 00:56:40.300
What if they find out that he's immune?

755
00:56:41.200 --> 00:56:44.100
I'm gonna call Galeano.
tell him what's going on. Okay?

756
00:56:44.300 --> 00:56:45.300
Oh. Ben.

757
00:56:45.500 --> 00:56:47.300
And then we'll go and find Oliver.

758
00:56:50.300 --> 00:56:51.900
- <i>Yeah?</i>
- Hi. it's Ben.

759
00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:54.300
- <i>Did you reach Fort Detrick?</i>
- Yeah. we're here.

760
00:56:54.400 --> 00:56:56.200
<i>You wouldn't believe this place. man.</i>

761
00:56:56.300 --> 00:56:59.100
So much Nobel gold here.
you'd think you were at Fort Knox.

762
00:56:59.200 --> 00:57:02.600
<i>Nadler. Stamets. Bohm. Dworetzky.</i>

763
00:57:02.700 --> 00:57:04.600
They're flying people in constantly.

764
00:57:04.800 --> 00:57:07.000
Helicopters and planes
are swarming all around.

765
00:57:07.200 --> 00:57:11.800
Somebody realized there's a war going on.
and the only way to win it is in a lab.

766
00:57:11.900 --> 00:57:14.800
<i>They know what they're doing.</i>
<i>They got a first-stage protocol.</i>

767
00:57:15.100 --> 00:57:17.300
- They've isolated it?
- They can test for it.

768
00:57:17.500 --> 00:57:20.500
- Do you have it?
- I'll know in about an hour.

769
00:57:21.200 --> 00:57:22.200
<i>Listen. Steven.</i>

770
00:57:22.400 --> 00:57:27.300
Remember the woman we saw by
the roadblock? She had ADEM as a child.

771
00:57:27.500 --> 00:57:29.200
Substantia alba. Interesting.

772
00:57:29.300 --> 00:57:32.900
What I'm thinking is that if she's immune.
maybe we have causality.

773
00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:34.200
<i>I get it. I see it.</i>

774
00:57:34.400 --> 00:57:36.700
The ADEM affects the neuron structure.

775
00:57:36.800 --> 00:57:39.500
If that were true.
we could create a conjugate vaccine.

776
00:57:39.600 --> 00:57:41.900
If possible.
we could reverse the process.

777
00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:45.200
But we need verification. We need
blood work. biopsy. MRI. PET scan.

778
00:57:45.400 --> 00:57:47.600
- <i>Do we know she's alive?</i>
- We got an alternative.

779
00:57:47.800 --> 00:57:50.400
Carol's son. Oliver. He had ADEM.

780
00:57:50.600 --> 00:57:54.400
- Wait. Wait. are you still downtown?
- Yeah. we're in Carol's office.

781
00:57:54.600 --> 00:57:57.800
- Okay. you need to get out of there now.
- Why?

782
00:58:05.800 --> 00:58:08.600
Okay. Yeah. Bye.

783
00:58:08.800 --> 00:58:11.200
- Carol.
- That was Ollie. He's in Baltimore.

784
00:58:11.300 --> 00:58:12.600
Baltimore?

785
00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:15.900
Tucker's taken him to his mother's house.
I don't know why.

786
00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:18.000
Well. I think I know why.

787
00:58:18.100 --> 00:58:20.800
That roadblock. that's the beginning.
They've set up quarantine.

788
00:58:21.000 --> 00:58:23.100
Stay within the barricade.

789
00:58:23.200 --> 00:58:25.700
They're sealing off this part of the city.

790
00:58:25.900 --> 00:58:28.100
- No. I have to get to Baltimore.
- Yeah. I know.

791
00:58:28.200 --> 00:58:29.400
I have to get to Oliver.

792
00:58:29.600 --> 00:58:32.800
I promised you that we're gonna find Oliver.
You gotta trust me.

793
00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.100
Stay down.

794
00:58:37.200 --> 00:58:39.000
We'll do what it takes
to get through this.

795
00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:42.700
- Hey!
- Hey!

796
00:58:45.900 --> 00:58:47.500
Ben.

797
00:58:49.600 --> 00:58:51.000
I have it.

798
00:58:53.400 --> 00:58:55.900
Tucker held me down and I have it.

799
00:59:10.700 --> 00:59:14.300
Oh. God. I'm so afraid
I'm gonna fall asleep.

800
00:59:15.200 --> 00:59:18.000
I'm so afraid I'm gonna lose him.
I'm gonna lose you.

801
00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:22.800
I'm gonna lose everything that matters.

802
00:59:23.400 --> 00:59:26.200
No. no. no. you won't.

803
00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:29.500
You can go for a week without sleep.
and then we'll find a pharmacy.

804
00:59:29.800 --> 00:59:32.400
We'll do whatever it takes
so you can stay awake.

805
00:59:32.600 --> 00:59:37.000
I just want you to know
there is nothing I wouldn't do for you.

806
00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:41.000
Nothing.

807
00:59:44.900 --> 00:59:48.700
Carol. get out! Get out. We've gotta
get out of the car now. Get out!

808
00:59:50.200 --> 00:59:52.000
- Ben!
- I'll find you!

809
00:59:52.200 --> 00:59:53.800
- No!
- Find Oliver!

810
00:59:54.600 --> 00:59:55.800
I love you!

811
01:00:13.800 --> 01:00:15.500
I need to see your ID. ma'am.

812
01:00:24.400 --> 01:00:26.800
Never mind. Good evening. ma'am.

813
01:00:35.800 --> 01:00:39.000
<i>Train number 171 receiving on Track 5.</i>

814
01:00:40.100 --> 01:00:42.200
<i>Service from Washington to Baltimore.</i>

815
01:00:42.300 --> 01:00:44.600
Mom. Mom.

816
01:00:45.700 --> 01:00:47.400
Come with me.

817
01:01:03.400 --> 01:01:04.800
This will help you sleep.

818
01:01:06.400 --> 01:01:08.400
We have a place for you to lie down.

819
01:01:49.200 --> 01:01:50.400
No!

820
01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:41.800
Gene.

821
01:02:42.900 --> 01:02:44.700
Where are your parents. Gene?

822
01:02:44.800 --> 01:02:48.900
They didn't survive.
Your family is my family now.

823
01:02:49.400 --> 01:02:52.700
Enough pretending. Come. Sleep.

824
01:02:53.700 --> 01:02:57.200
I don't wanna go out there
with all of them watching me.

825
01:02:57.600 --> 01:03:00.700
I just wanna do it alone.
I'll do it. I just...

826
01:03:02.200 --> 01:03:06.000
You can lock me in here.
I just wanna be alone...

827
01:03:17.200 --> 01:03:19.200
<i>Train 56. the Vermonter...</i>

828
01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:23.700
<i>... with service to Baltimore. Philadelphia.</i>
<i>New York. New Haven...</i>

829
01:03:23.900 --> 01:03:27.300
<i>... White River. and with final destination</i>
<i>of Saint Albans...</i>

830
01:03:27.400 --> 01:03:29.800
<i>... now boarding at Track 4.</i>

831
01:03:41.900 --> 01:03:45.200
Hello. Carol. Gene.
It's good to see you.

832
01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:55.700
Taxis are just outside.

833
01:04:02.600 --> 01:04:04.200
Here you are.

834
01:04:04.400 --> 01:04:07.700
And with Carol. Come in.

835
01:04:07.900 --> 01:04:09.900
I hope you didn't eat on the train.

836
01:04:11.400 --> 01:04:12.600
I'm making cutlets.

837
01:04:12.700 --> 01:04:14.900
Will Oliver be joining us?

838
01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:18.200
I imagine so. I'm sure he'll be finished soon.
He'll let us know.

839
01:04:18.400 --> 01:04:20.300
<i>North Korean Leader Kim Jong-Il</i>...

840
01:04:20.400 --> 01:04:22.100
Mother.

841
01:04:22.200 --> 01:04:24.500
- <i>the first unilateral</i>
<i>nuclear-disarmament treaty.</i>

842
01:04:24.700 --> 01:04:27.300
<i>North Korea is the final country</i>
<i>to sign the treaty.</i>

843
01:04:27.500 --> 01:04:31.100
<i>Leaders of Pakistan and India met to</i>
<i>celebrate the region's new peace accord...</i>

844
01:04:31.300 --> 01:04:36.300
<i>... finally ending the bloody border dispute</i>
<i>that has cost thousands of innocent lives.</i>

845
01:04:36.400 --> 01:04:40.200
<i>In China. several more political prisoners.</i>
<i>including Gao Yaojie...</i>

846
01:04:40.300 --> 01:04:42.800
<i>... were released.</i>
<i>reuniting them with their families.</i>

847
01:04:42.900 --> 01:04:45.100
<i>Today marks the third</i>
<i>consecutive week...</i>

848
01:04:45.300 --> 01:04:50.100
<i>... no suicide attacks exploded near the U.S.</i>
<i>embassy or public buildings in the region.</i>

849
01:04:50.300 --> 01:04:53.300
<i>A suicide blast would be the first</i>
<i>in Kabul since December.</i>

850
01:04:53.400 --> 01:04:55.000
This is Dr. Bennell.

851
01:04:55.200 --> 01:04:57.000
<i>Carol. it's Ben.</i>

852
01:04:58.000 --> 01:04:59.900
Yes. what can I do for you. Sally?

853
01:05:00.100 --> 01:05:02.100
<i>Are you in mixed company?</i>

854
01:05:03.200 --> 01:05:04.400
Yes. I am.

855
01:05:04.600 --> 01:05:08.600
<i>Okay. look. I'm on my way. It'll take me</i>
<i>a couple of hours to get to you.</i>

856
01:05:08.800 --> 01:05:10.600
<i>What part of the city are you in?</i>

857
01:05:11.400 --> 01:05:14.900
<i>Look. just stop me when I say it.</i>
<i>Federal Hill? Fells Point?</i>

858
01:05:17.100 --> 01:05:19.700
- <i>City Center?</i>
- Yes. that's right.

859
01:05:19.900 --> 01:05:24.300
<i>Good. Text me the instant you're on</i>
<i>your own. we'll find a place to meet.</i>

860
01:05:24.400 --> 01:05:26.100
Thank you for calling. Sally.

861
01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:32.800
<i>Today marked the end of</i>
<i>the humanitarian crisis in Darfur...</i>

862
01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:36.300
<i>... with the Janjaweed party agreeing</i>
<i>to a complete and total cease-fire.</i>

863
01:05:36.800 --> 01:05:38.500
Hello?

864
01:05:39.700 --> 01:05:41.200
Thank you.

865
01:05:43.300 --> 01:05:44.900
They're ready for you downstairs.

866
01:05:45.100 --> 01:05:47.700
<i>President Bush and President Chavez</i>
<i>met today...</i>

867
01:05:47.900 --> 01:05:51.400
<i>... to further strengthen ties</i>
<i>between the U.S. and Venezuela.</i>

868
01:05:51.500 --> 01:05:56.300
<i>A deal that initially provided heating fuel</i>
<i>to New York's five boroughs...</i>

869
01:05:57.100 --> 01:05:59.900
May I be excused for a moment. please?

870
01:06:04.200 --> 01:06:09.200
<i>The $400-billion program would be the</i>
<i>largest fiscal spending since the Iraqi War.</i>

871
01:06:09.200 --> 01:06:13.600
<i>Pharmaceutical companies have agreed</i>
<i>to start issuing free AIDS vaccines...</i>

872
01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:18.400
<i>... to all afflicted Third World countries.</i>
<i>effective immediately.</i>

873
01:06:50.900 --> 01:06:52.300
It's a pickle. isn't it?

874
01:06:54.200 --> 01:06:55.700
What did you say?

875
01:06:57.100 --> 01:06:58.500
I said...

876
01:07:05.400 --> 01:07:06.900
I thought you were one of them.

877
01:07:07.100 --> 01:07:09.400
No. Never.

878
01:07:11.200 --> 01:07:13.200
I thought you were sleeping.

879
01:07:13.400 --> 01:07:15.900
I did fall asleep. I did.

880
01:07:17.100 --> 01:07:19.900
Last night and this morning.

881
01:07:20.800 --> 01:07:23.000
Does that mean something bad?

882
01:07:23.600 --> 01:07:25.100
Oliver...

883
01:07:25.800 --> 01:07:28.200
...that means you're immune. baby.

884
01:07:28.600 --> 01:07:30.600
That means you're immune.

885
01:07:35.800 --> 01:07:38.900
I'm gonna get you out of here. okay?

886
01:07:49.400 --> 01:07:50.900
Come on.

887
01:07:52.200 --> 01:07:54.800
<i>On the streets of Baghdad.</i>
<i>there was jubilation...</i>

888
01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:57.200
<i>... as the last of U.S. forces withdrew...</i>

889
01:07:57.400 --> 01:08:00.000
<i>... marking the end</i>
<i>of the occupation of Iraq.</i>

890
01:08:00.200 --> 01:08:04.500
<i>Iraqi President al-Sadr was on hand</i>
<i>to commemorate the occasion...</i>

891
01:08:04.600 --> 01:08:07.800
<i>... and praised Sunni. Shiah.</i>
<i>Kurd and Turkoman...</i>

892
01:08:14.300 --> 01:08:16.200
Security.

893
01:08:17.800 --> 01:08:20.300
Yes. he's outside the building.

894
01:08:22.900 --> 01:08:24.000
Ma'am?

895
01:08:25.000 --> 01:08:26.300
Run.

896
01:08:46.600 --> 01:08:47.700
Run.

897
01:09:15.800 --> 01:09:17.400
Mom!

898
01:09:18.200 --> 01:09:19.500
Here!

899
01:09:58.500 --> 01:10:00.200
Find the door.

900
01:10:14.300 --> 01:10:16.000
Son?

901
01:10:17.800 --> 01:10:19.900
This is your father.

902
01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:23.700
Son?

903
01:10:24.300 --> 01:10:26.100
Where are you?

904
01:10:35.200 --> 01:10:38.100
I saw you sleeping. Oliver.

905
01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:44.800
There is only one reason
you'd be trying to hide from me.

906
01:10:47.500 --> 01:10:50.400
I don't understand your resistance. Carol.

907
01:10:54.300 --> 01:10:58.200
You give people pills
to make their lives better.

908
01:10:58.800 --> 01:11:01.400
How is that so different
from what we're doing?

909
01:11:03.300 --> 01:11:04.300
It's a pity.

910
01:11:07.400 --> 01:11:10.100
I had hoped we could be a family again.

911
01:11:15.600 --> 01:11:19.300
Do you know why
our marriage failed. Carol?

912
01:11:21.500 --> 01:11:23.000
Because I was third.

913
01:11:24.200 --> 01:11:27.300
The thing you loved the most
was your son.

914
01:11:29.300 --> 01:11:31.700
After him came your job.

915
01:11:35.200 --> 01:11:37.200
After that came me.

916
01:11:41.300 --> 01:11:44.300
I was third on your list.

917
01:11:47.700 --> 01:11:49.700
That can't happen in our world.

918
01:11:52.600 --> 01:11:55.400
You remember what you said to me...

919
01:11:56.400 --> 01:11:59.400
...when you signed our divorce papers?

920
01:12:02.600 --> 01:12:06.100
"Sometimes we have to do things
which are painful...

921
01:12:07.100 --> 01:12:10.200
...to make our lives better."

922
01:12:11.700 --> 01:12:13.700
You were so right.

923
01:12:15.600 --> 01:12:16.600
Stop!

924
01:12:20.200 --> 01:12:24.400
You shouldn't hit your father.
You were raised better than that.

925
01:12:24.600 --> 01:12:28.400
I wish it didn't have to be like this. You
didn't wake up like you were supposed to.

926
01:12:30.900 --> 01:12:32.300
Are you all right? Yeah?

927
01:12:56.000 --> 01:12:58.100
Mom. what are we doing here?

928
01:12:58.300 --> 01:13:00.400
I'm just gonna look for some medicine.

929
01:13:00.600 --> 01:13:02.100
Come on.

930
01:13:02.700 --> 01:13:03.700
Come on.

931
01:13:12.500 --> 01:13:14.900
Mom. what kind of medicine
do you need?

932
01:13:15.100 --> 01:13:18.500
Something to keep me
from going to sleep.

933
01:13:21.300 --> 01:13:23.100
What'll happen if you do go to sleep?

934
01:13:24.500 --> 01:13:26.100
We have to make sure that I don't.

935
01:13:29.300 --> 01:13:32.600
Now. Ollie. I may need your help.

936
01:13:33.200 --> 01:13:34.500
You...

937
01:13:34.600 --> 01:13:38.200
You remember your cousin Zoe. don't you?
She had diabetes. remember?

938
01:13:38.300 --> 01:13:40.500
Sometimes she needed a shot.

939
01:13:40.600 --> 01:13:44.400
Well. if something happens
and I do fall asleep...

940
01:13:45.200 --> 01:13:48.600
...l'm gonna need you
to be very brave for me. okay?

941
01:13:48.700 --> 01:13:50.600
You can be brave. huh?

942
01:13:52.000 --> 01:13:56.800
If I fall asleep. I'm gonna need you
to give me a shot. Just like Zoe.

943
01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:00.100
But I'm gonna need you to put it...

944
01:14:00.800 --> 01:14:02.300
...here. in my heart.

945
01:14:03.800 --> 01:14:06.800
You just push the needle into my heart...

946
01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:08.600
...and you press the plunger.

947
01:14:08.700 --> 01:14:10.900
I know it seems scary. but...

948
01:14:11.100 --> 01:14:14.600
Anyway. it's just in case.
I'm gonna put it here. in my pocket.

949
01:14:14.700 --> 01:14:17.600
- You got that?
- Okay.

950
01:14:21.500 --> 01:14:25.500
I love you. Oliver. I love you so much.

951
01:14:35.700 --> 01:14:37.500
Ben. where are you?

952
01:14:37.700 --> 01:14:41.100
I'm outside Patterson Park.
about to go into a hospital.

953
01:14:41.300 --> 01:14:44.600
Galeano needs as much uncontaminated
blood as I can get. Where are you?

954
01:14:44.700 --> 01:14:47.400
We're in a pharmacy. South of Jefferson.

955
01:14:47.600 --> 01:14:49.200
- <i>Is Oliver with you?</i>
- Yeah.

956
01:14:49.400 --> 01:14:52.300
- <i>Good.</i>
- I'm really tired.

957
01:14:52.400 --> 01:14:55.600
- All right. I'll be there as soon as I can.
- Hurry.

958
01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:00.800
Mom. I'm kind of hungry.

959
01:15:01.000 --> 01:15:04.300
- You want some pretzels?
- Sure.

960
01:15:04.500 --> 01:15:07.700
- How about some nuts?
- Nuts. you mean like peanuts?

961
01:15:07.900 --> 01:15:09.300
- Almonds.
- Cashews.

962
01:15:10.200 --> 01:15:11.600
- Walnuts.
- Pecans.

963
01:15:11.700 --> 01:15:13.400
- Macadamias.
- Pistachios.

964
01:15:13.900 --> 01:15:16.000
Chestnuts. Pine nuts. Hazelnuts.

965
01:15:16.200 --> 01:15:17.500
All right. You win.

966
01:15:17.700 --> 01:15:20.000
Here. Want some?

967
01:15:24.400 --> 01:15:27.300
So is this what they mean
by "going nuts"?

968
01:15:28.500 --> 01:15:31.900
Yeah. Yeah. this is what they mean.

969
01:15:35.400 --> 01:15:38.100
<i>This is Dr. Ben Driscoll.</i>
<i>Leave a message after the tone.</i>

970
01:15:38.600 --> 01:15:40.400
Shit.

971
01:15:40.600 --> 01:15:42.600
Where are you?

972
01:15:46.600 --> 01:15:48.200
Hey. Mom. What's in here?

973
01:15:48.300 --> 01:15:49.900
No. no. No.

974
01:16:02.800 --> 01:16:04.200
Stay here.

975
01:16:55.300 --> 01:16:57.400
Whatever you hear. Oliver...

976
01:16:58.100 --> 01:17:01.200
...you must not open this door.
- Are there more of them in there?

977
01:17:01.300 --> 01:17:04.300
Don't open it. all right?

978
01:17:05.300 --> 01:17:07.700
- Is that real?
- It's just for protection...

979
01:17:07.900 --> 01:17:09.400
...till we get out of here.

980
01:17:10.200 --> 01:17:11.500
How much longer?

981
01:17:11.700 --> 01:17:14.200
It won't be long. It can't be.

982
01:17:23.200 --> 01:17:25.700
I'm not going to sleep.

983
01:17:26.600 --> 01:17:30.500
I know. Just rest.

984
01:17:32.600 --> 01:17:34.800
Don't go anywhere.

985
01:17:35.900 --> 01:17:37.700
I'm right here.

986
01:17:59.800 --> 01:18:01.500
Oh. God.

987
01:18:36.000 --> 01:18:38.800
Open the door. open the door!

988
01:18:39.400 --> 01:18:41.800
Please open the door!

989
01:18:50.900 --> 01:18:52.700
Hurry.

990
01:18:53.200 --> 01:18:57.100
Hurry. Ben. Please. hurry.

991
01:18:57.400 --> 01:18:58.400
Hurry.

992
01:19:27.500 --> 01:19:30.500
Mom? Mom?

993
01:19:30.700 --> 01:19:32.300
Mom!

994
01:19:34.500 --> 01:19:35.700
Mom?

995
01:19:36.100 --> 01:19:37.400
Mom!

996
01:19:39.400 --> 01:19:41.300
Mom!

997
01:19:41.700 --> 01:19:43.000
Mom!

998
01:19:43.300 --> 01:19:45.600
Mom. wake up! Wake up. Mom!

999
01:19:47.400 --> 01:19:50.600
Mom! Mom. wake up!

1000
01:19:51.900 --> 01:19:53.600
Wake up.

1001
01:20:10.700 --> 01:20:14.400
Oliver. Oh. my God. Oliver.

1002
01:20:14.600 --> 01:20:16.300
Oh. I'm so sorry.

1003
01:20:16.400 --> 01:20:18.500
It's okay. It's okay.

1004
01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:23.100
- It's okay. Mom. It's okay.
- I'm so sorry.

1005
01:20:26.700 --> 01:20:28.800
We gotta get out of here.

1006
01:20:55.000 --> 01:20:56.700
Ben.

1007
01:20:57.100 --> 01:20:58.100
Where have you been?

1008
01:20:58.300 --> 01:21:01.400
I was at the hospital.
There was some trouble. but I'm here now.

1009
01:21:01.500 --> 01:21:05.600
Oh. God. Oh. my God.
you wouldn't believe what's happened.

1010
01:21:05.800 --> 01:21:07.100
Everything's gonna be fine.

1011
01:21:07.300 --> 01:21:09.600
I know how afraid you've been. Carol.

1012
01:21:09.800 --> 01:21:12.800
But you don't have to be
afraid ever again.

1013
01:21:16.300 --> 01:21:18.300
Oh. no. No. no. no.

1014
01:21:19.700 --> 01:21:22.300
- No. no. no.
- No. just... Just listen to me.

1015
01:21:22.700 --> 01:21:24.200
No. not you.

1016
01:21:24.600 --> 01:21:26.600
- Dr. Ben.
- Hey. Ollie.

1017
01:21:26.700 --> 01:21:28.900
Get away from him! You come here!

1018
01:21:29.100 --> 01:21:30.400
- Carol.
- Get away!

1019
01:21:30.600 --> 01:21:33.400
- Get away from us!
- Carol. look at yourself.

1020
01:21:34.400 --> 01:21:37.000
Is this who you are?
Is this who you want to be?

1021
01:21:38.300 --> 01:21:40.200
We were wrong to fight them.

1022
01:21:40.300 --> 01:21:41.700
No. No.

1023
01:21:41.900 --> 01:21:44.100
- Remember our trip up to Colorado?
- Shut up.

1024
01:21:44.300 --> 01:21:47.300
- Do you remember the aspen grove?
- Shut up. Shut up!

1025
01:21:47.500 --> 01:21:49.400
How beautiful and peaceful it was.

1026
01:21:49.500 --> 01:21:53.100
- Remember what you said to me?
- I didn't say anything to you!

1027
01:21:53.300 --> 01:21:56.900
You wondered what it'd be like
if people could live more like those trees...

1028
01:21:57.100 --> 01:21:59.900
...completely connected
with each other. in harmony.

1029
01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:02.400
As one.

1030
01:22:02.600 --> 01:22:06.600
You're not Ben. I know you're not Ben.

1031
01:22:06.900 --> 01:22:08.000
I'm not just Ben...

1032
01:22:09.400 --> 01:22:11.100
...l'm more than Ben.

1033
01:22:11.300 --> 01:22:13.500
Stop! Don't open that door!

1034
01:22:15.500 --> 01:22:19.700
Have you seen the television?
Have you read the newspapers?

1035
01:22:19.900 --> 01:22:21.900
See what's happening.
what we're offering?

1036
01:22:22.200 --> 01:22:27.000
A world without war. without poverty.
without murder. without rape.

1037
01:22:27.200 --> 01:22:28.400
A world without suffering.

1038
01:22:29.400 --> 01:22:33.400
Because in our world. no one can
hurt each other or exploit each other...

1039
01:22:33.600 --> 01:22:37.500
...or destroy each other.
because in our world. there is no other.

1040
01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:39.900
You know it's right. Carol.

1041
01:22:40.400 --> 01:22:43.000
Deep down inside.
you know that fighting us...

1042
01:22:43.300 --> 01:22:46.300
...is fighting for all the wrong things.

1043
01:22:47.900 --> 01:22:49.600
Carol...

1044
01:22:49.800 --> 01:22:51.500
...you know it's true.

1045
01:22:52.100 --> 01:22:54.500
Our world is a better world.

1046
01:22:58.400 --> 01:22:59.700
What about Ollie?

1047
01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:03.800
- We'll take care of him.
- How?

1048
01:23:05.300 --> 01:23:07.700
Tell me how!

1049
01:23:08.600 --> 01:23:10.700
There is no room
for someone who is immune.

1050
01:23:10.900 --> 01:23:12.300
Mom? Mom!

1051
01:23:12.800 --> 01:23:14.000
Don't touch my child!

1052
01:23:14.200 --> 01:23:16.600
No one touches my child!

1053
01:23:18.300 --> 01:23:20.700
- Will you kill us all?
- lf I have to.

1054
01:23:20.800 --> 01:23:23.000
- We have to stop you.
- You can't stop me.

1055
01:23:23.200 --> 01:23:24.700
But we have to try.

1056
01:23:33.800 --> 01:23:35.400
Could you shoot me so easily?

1057
01:23:37.700 --> 01:23:39.300
No.

1058
01:23:42.000 --> 01:23:43.400
Run!

1059
01:23:44.100 --> 01:23:46.300
Run! Let's go!

1060
01:23:48.400 --> 01:23:50.500
Get in the car. Go!

1061
01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:07.000
That's Ben's.

1062
01:24:09.500 --> 01:24:11.400
- Hello?
- <i>Carol. is that you?</i>

1063
01:24:11.700 --> 01:24:14.000
- Steven?
- <i>We're waiting for Ben. Is he with you?</i>

1064
01:24:14.200 --> 01:24:16.600
Oh. God. Steven.
Steven. we need your help.

1065
01:24:16.700 --> 01:24:18.500
<i>Carol. where are you?</i>

1066
01:24:32.400 --> 01:24:34.400
<i>Carol. what is happening? Carol.</i>

1067
01:24:37.400 --> 01:24:39.600
<i>Carol. where are you? Carol?</i>

1068
01:24:40.100 --> 01:24:41.500
Mom?

1069
01:24:48.300 --> 01:24:49.500
<i>Carol!</i>

1070
01:24:50.900 --> 01:24:52.100
<i>Carol!</i>

1071
01:24:53.600 --> 01:24:55.100
Mom!

1072
01:24:58.300 --> 01:25:00.400
Mom! Wake up!

1073
01:25:01.800 --> 01:25:03.400
Mom!

1074
01:25:05.800 --> 01:25:07.100
Look! Mom!

1075
01:25:07.900 --> 01:25:08.900
Look!

1076
01:25:12.300 --> 01:25:13.500
No!

1077
01:25:14.200 --> 01:25:15.300
Go. go!

1078
01:25:29.200 --> 01:25:31.500
Ollie. the phone. Get the phone!

1079
01:25:50.600 --> 01:25:52.500
<i>Carol. what's going on? Carol!</i>

1080
01:25:54.500 --> 01:25:56.000
<i>Carol. where are you?</i>

1081
01:26:02.600 --> 01:26:05.000
<i>I'm in a helicopter. We're over the city.</i>

1082
01:26:05.100 --> 01:26:07.800
He says he's in a helicopter!
Where are we?

1083
01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:11.300
I don't know.
I think we're heading south on 13th.

1084
01:26:11.500 --> 01:26:12.500
South on 13th!

1085
01:26:55.600 --> 01:26:59.200
<i>You need to get to the Carlson Building.</i>
<i>It has a landing pad.</i>

1086
01:27:00.300 --> 01:27:04.000
- We're almost there. Are you close?
- Yeah. we're a couple of blocks away.

1087
01:27:06.200 --> 01:27:08.100
Mom. I hear it!

1088
01:27:11.500 --> 01:27:12.800
There!

1089
01:27:13.200 --> 01:27:14.800
Carol. you're almost there.

1090
01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:18.800
<i>There's a parking garage under the building.</i>
<i>Couple blocks up ahead on your right.</i>

1091
01:27:22.200 --> 01:27:24.400
- Mom!
- Get down!

1092
01:27:25.100 --> 01:27:26.800
Oh. no.

1093
01:27:37.400 --> 01:27:39.300
Turn right. Carol.

1094
01:27:39.500 --> 01:27:40.600
Turn right! Now!

1095
01:27:52.300 --> 01:27:53.400
Get to the roof!

1096
01:27:58.300 --> 01:27:59.600
Let's go.

1097
01:28:21.500 --> 01:28:23.000
- Ollie. you okay?
- Yeah.

1098
01:28:40.600 --> 01:28:41.600
They're coming!

1099
01:29:21.100 --> 01:29:22.800
Move out! Set perimeter!

1100
01:29:26.200 --> 01:29:28.300
Run! Come on. you're almost there!

1101
01:29:31.900 --> 01:29:33.500
- Go. go. go! Go!
- Move!

1102
01:29:42.400 --> 01:29:44.000
Clear!

1103
01:29:50.700 --> 01:29:52.300
You're okay.

1104
01:30:09.500 --> 01:30:12.400
<i>Scientists are reporting</i>
<i>that identifying the immunity gene...</i>

1105
01:30:12.600 --> 01:30:15.300
<i>... is the first step in creating</i>
<i>a cure to the pandemic.</i>

1106
01:30:15.400 --> 01:30:18.200
<i>Survivors are using every means</i>
<i>to spread the vaccine...</i>

1107
01:30:18.300 --> 01:30:21.900
<i>... to as many people as possible.</i>
<i>Food and water supplies...</i>

1108
01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:25.000
<i>Pockets of the immune began to grow</i>
<i>across the country...</i>

1109
01:30:25.100 --> 01:30:27.000
<i>... retaking control of major cities...</i>

1110
01:30:27.100 --> 01:30:29.800
<i>On the anniversary of</i>
<i>the space shuttle</i> Patriot <i>disaster...</i>

1111
01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:32.700
<i>... leading scientists convened</i>
<i>in Washington today...</i>

1112
01:30:32.900 --> 01:30:37.900
<i>... to update the president on the continued</i>
<i>efforts to eradicate the global pandemic.</i>

1113
01:30:38.100 --> 01:30:41.400
- Dr. Galeano!
- Is this the final word?

1114
01:30:41.600 --> 01:30:44.500
- The virus. will it spread again?
- The situation's under control.

1115
01:30:44.700 --> 01:30:48.100
Inoculation centers throughout the globe
are experiencing success...

1116
01:30:48.300 --> 01:30:50.900
...in curing and immunizing
their populations.

1117
01:30:51.100 --> 01:30:52.600
Why was it so easy to cure?

1118
01:30:52.600 --> 01:30:54.700
The alien virus has
no real defense system.

1119
01:30:54.800 --> 01:30:58.100
Once we isolated the vaccine.
the result was inevitable.

1120
01:30:58.400 --> 01:31:00.000
How many people are still infected?

1121
01:31:00.200 --> 01:31:03.300
- We're unsure. but the number is shrinking.
- What about memory loss?

1122
01:31:03.500 --> 01:31:06.600
We believe that the way
the entity plugged itself into our brain...

1123
01:31:06.800 --> 01:31:08.700
...was so different
from how we're wired...

1124
01:31:08.900 --> 01:31:12.000
...that the mind interpreted the experience
as unconsciousness.

1125
01:31:12.200 --> 01:31:15.300
Which explains why the cured
have no recollection of recent events.

1126
01:31:15.500 --> 01:31:19.200
- They experienced it as though asleep.
- Does this mean it's over?

1127
01:31:19.300 --> 01:31:21.200
- Over?
- The alien virus.

1128
01:31:21.400 --> 01:31:23.300
Has it been eradicated?

1129
01:31:23.500 --> 01:31:26.100
Well. pick up a newspaper.

1130
01:31:26.300 --> 01:31:29.600
For better or worse. we're human again.

1131
01:31:33.300 --> 01:31:35.300
Ollie. hurry up. You're gonna be late.

1132
01:31:36.900 --> 01:31:39.200
- Where's Gene?
- Coming.

1133
01:31:39.300 --> 01:31:41.100
What did I tell you about that thing?

1134
01:31:41.300 --> 01:31:43.600
But I almost got it. Oh. no!

1135
01:31:44.100 --> 01:31:47.200
- You can have it back after school.
- All right.

1136
01:31:47.400 --> 01:31:49.600
Have a nice day. Love you.

1137
01:31:52.200 --> 01:31:53.200
I love you too.

1138
01:31:55.100 --> 01:31:57.300
- See you later.
- See you.

1139
01:32:01.800 --> 01:32:05.100
Eighty-three more deaths in Baghdad.

1140
01:32:08.000 --> 01:32:10.000
Is it ever gonna end?

1141
01:32:12.300 --> 01:32:16.200
<i>In the right situation. we are all capable</i>
<i>of the most terrible crimes.</i>

1142
01:32:16.400 --> 01:32:18.800
<i>To imagine a world</i>
<i>where this was not so...</i>

1143
01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:21.600
<i>... where every crisis did not result</i>
<i>in new atrocities...</i>

1144
01:32:21.800 --> 01:32:24.700
<i>... where every newspaper</i>
<i>is not full of war and violence...</i>

1145
01:32:24.800 --> 01:32:31.100
<i>Well. this is to imagine a world where</i>
<i>human beings cease to be human.</i>

1146
01:39:21.500 --> 01:39:23.500
[ENGLISH]
